## Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` :

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/646a2190f7685ece82b7cbb7ccf7d44ba4cfbefa/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L165
https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/646a2190f7685ece82b7cbb7ccf7d44ba4cfbefa/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L175

## Regression

This is not a regression.

</details>

In record structs with positional parameters, if you create a constructor which in turn calls the synthesised parameterless constructor, the compiler will emit code which either attempts an out of bounds memory access, or results in a type confusion. 

The OOB read is caused when the positional parameters outnumber the constructor's arguments. The below code will compile, and throw an `System.InvalidProgramException` at runtime.
```cs
record struct Parameters(int i, int j)
{
    public Parameters(int i)
        : this()
    {
    }
}
```
And the generated IL:
```
.method public hidebysig specialname rtspecialname 
	instance void .ctor (
		int32 i
	) cil managed 
{
	// Method begins at RVA 0x2094
	// Header size: 1
	// Code size: 15 (0xf)
	.maxstack 8

	IL_0000: ldarg.0
	IL_0001: ldarg.1
	IL_0002: stfld int32 Parameters::'<i>k__BackingField'
	IL_0007: ldarg.0
	IL_0008: ldarg.2 /*Error near IL_0008: ldarg 2 (out-of-bounds)*/
	IL_0009: stfld int32 Parameters::'<j>k__BackingField'
	IL_000e: ret
} // end of method Parameters::.ctor
```
More concerning, if the number of arguments are equal the constructor will write the values to the corresponding positional parameters, regardless of type; essentially a bitwise conversion. This will compile and run to completion, despite invoking undefined (but reproducible) behaviour.
```cs
record struct TypeConfusion(ulong i)
{
    public TypeConfusion(string s)
        : this()
    {
    }
}

string s = "test";

 // Confusion between the string's pointer to ulong; the address of the string is now held in tc.i
TypeConfusion tc = new(s);

// We can prove this by comparing against the address of s[0].
fixed (char* c = s.AsSpan())
{
    Console.WriteLine(((ulong)c) - 12 == tc.i); // -12 to account for the object header.
}
```

And the constructor's IL:
```
.method public hidebysig specialname rtspecialname 
	instance void .ctor (
		string s
	) cil managed 
{
	// Method begins at RVA 0x20b4
	// Header size: 1
	// Code size: 8 (0x8)
	.maxstack 8

        // i = (ulong)(long)s;
	IL_0000: ldarg.0
	IL_0001: ldarg.1
	IL_0002: stfld uint64 TypeConfusion::'<i>k__BackingField'
	IL_0007: ret
} // end of method TypeConfusion::.ctor
```
This could potentially open the door to many security vulnerabilities, including possible ACE.

